Now I can see the issue. Looking at the `IntersectionObserver` setup (lines 288-316):

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  const node = containerRef.current;
  if (!node) return;

  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
    ([entry]) => {
      const visible = entry.isIntersecting;
      if (activePage === "chats") {
        setIsInView(visible);
        if (visible) {
          runAnimation(activeCaseRef.current);
        } else {
          clearAll();
        }
      } else {
        setIsInView(false);
        clearAll();
      }
    },
    { threshold: 0.2 },
  );

  observer.observe(node);

  return () => {
    observer.disconnect();
    clearAll();
  };
}, [activePage, clearAll, runAnimation]);
```

When the user navigates to a different page, the effect re-runs and immediately sets `isInView` to false, which removes the animation classes from the demo window even though the element is still visible on screen.

The real issue is that `isInView` is being used to control visibility, but it's getting reset whenever the page changes. I need to separate the intersection observer logic from the page navigation logic so the demo stays visible and animated when it's actually in the viewport, regardless of which page is active. the entrance animations should trigger once when the section becomes visible, then persist regardless of page navigation. I need to decouple the viewport intersection state from the animation control logic — keep `isInView` reflecting actual visibility in the viewport, and use a separate flag to track whether the chat animation specifically should be running based on the current page. I see the issue now—when `activePage` changes away from "chats", the observer still fires and sets `isInView` based on actual intersection, but I need to make sure `clearAll()` stops the animations without resetting the entrance flag. The real problem is that `isInView` should only ever be set to true by the intersection observer when the element actually enters the viewport, and once true, it stays true for the entrance animation. The page-switching logic should only control whether animations run, not whether the element has been seen. The issue is that these entrance animations are one-time CSS effects, so once they play, replaying them when `isInView` toggles feels jarring. The real problem the user reported is that navigating away from the chat page hides the demo window entirely because `isInView` gets forced to false. I need to decouple visibility from the animation trigger—the demo should stay visible even on non-chat pages, but the chat animation should only run when actually on the chats page. I'm revising the observer to handle this by checking the page context before deciding what to do.

Refining the observer logic... I'm tracing through the page transition logic more carefully. When switching from "chats" to "workflows", the cleanup fires and clears the animation, which is correct. The issue is that I removed the `else` branch that was setting `isInView` to false when the element scrolls out of view, so now the visibility state might not update properly in all cases.

But actually, the cleanup function already handles clearing the timers when the effect re-runs, and the observer's false case handles when scrolling out of view. So I just need to remove the explicit `setIsInView(false)` from the non-chats branch and rely on the cleanup and observer logic to manage the state correctly.

Simplifying the observer logic...

Writing observer code... The IntersectionObserver callback fires asynchronously, so there's a timing gap when switching pages, but the new observer will correctly determine the intersection state when it eventually fires. Since the animation only starts when `activePage === "chats"`, the edge case resolves itself—if we're on a different page, `isInView` just updates without triggering anything. I'm satisfied this approach handles all the scenarios correctly, so I'll move forward with implementing it.

